parking mad Man tells of shock at receiving letter from cops about an 11-year-old parking fine 
Jim O’Brien, 42 was baffled to receive the letter about a fine for parking on a double yellow line in December 2006 By Michael Doyle 15th April 2017, 7:00 am Updated: 16th April 2017, 3:10 am Click to share on Facebook (Opens in new window) Comments A MAN has told of his shock at receiving a letter from cops saying they are going to court on his behalf to quash an 11-year-old parking fine. 
Jim O’Brien, 42, said he was baffled when it arrived yesterday. 2 Jim O’Brien holds up the parking fine 11 years later 
The letter told him police were appealing a fine for parking on a double yellow line on December 14, 2006. 
But Mr O’Brien, from Clondalkin, Dublin, said the most bizarre thing was he has no recollection of the “offence”. 
He told the Irish Sun: “I’m trying to contact them but no one’s picking up the phones and I got an automated response to my email saying someone would be in touch within three months. “I don’t know whether I’m due a refund or what but I don’t remember this incident at all. If a number of parking fines were wrong I had no idea they went back so far with them — this was 2006. 
“The only thing I can think of was I used to work as a courier delivering medical products and such back then so maybe it has something to do with that.” 2 Jim O’Brien received the parking fine 11 years after the offence took place 
The letter says: “I’m writing to you following a review conducted by An Garda Siochana (Irish police force) of prosecutions taken in respect of Fixed Charge Offences. 
“It has been identified that the correct procedures were not followed by An Garda Siochana in respect of the court conviction imposed on you on 14/12/2006 in relation to Double Yellow Lines-Driver-Parking. 
“Subject to your consent, An Garda Siochana will commence a process of appealing the conviction on your behalf.” 
It asks the recipient to fill out an enclosed form and return it in a self-addressed envelope. It also apologises and says it will do everything possible to redress the issue as quickly as possible. 
A police spokesman said yesterday that if anyone has an issue with their fixed charge notices they should contact FCN.Helpline@garda.ie.
